'''Explanatory notes'''

{{notes
| notes =

{{efn
| name = coin
| {{harvnb|Waddell|1886|p=392}}. In Joseph Addison Waddell's ''Annals of Augusta County, Virginia, With Reminiscences Illustrative of the Vicissitudes of Its Pioneer Settlers'' (1886), Waddell states that a descendant of Jones had in their possession an old coin and on its paper wrapping was a note written by Jones: "This is the patrimony I received from my mother. From my father I received nothing."
}}

{{efn
| name = first 
| {{harvnb|Munske|2004|p=39}}. In [[Hu Maxwell]]'s ''History of Hampshire County, West Virginia: From Its Earliest Settlement to the Present'' (1897), he states that Archibald Wager was the inaugural Clerk of Court for Hampshire County, serving from 1755 to 1757. Historian Wilmer L. Kerns in ''Hampshire County, West Virginia, 1754<U+2013>2004'' (2004) contends that Jones was in fact the first Clerk of Court for Hampshire County, as there was no record keeping in the county until the start of Jones's tenure as Clerk of Court in 1757.
}}

{{efn
| name = election
| {{harvnb|Waddell|1886|p=393}}. In Waddell's ''Annals of Augusta County, Virginia, With Reminiscences Illustrative of the Vicissitudes of Its Pioneer Settlers'' (1886), Waddell remarks of Lewis and Jones prior to their election to represent Rockingham County in the [[Virginia Ratifying Convention]]: "Mr. Lewis was a popular man while Mr. Jones was not, and it is related that in a public speech before the election, the latter declined the support of 'the rascals' who, he understood, proposed to vote for him because of his association with the former." 
}}

